<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=1993138040&t=artid%3d16aa80f9-c38b-47bd-a59c-3bbda23023cc%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=1993138040&t=artid%3d16aa80f9-c38b-47bd-a59c-3bbda23023cc%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>It took her six years before she finally could get her own stand in 2006 at the Mansel Road Market in Durban.She told Daily Sun her husband died in 1998 while three of her five children were still at school and she had to start doing everything for herself.“It was very hard and I struggled a lot,” she said. “In 2000, I realised that since I have a talent to make isigege, I should sell them to educate my children.”She said she started making them at home in Bizana. “My neighbour told me there was big demand in Durban and late in 2000 I decided to come here and sell them,” she said.She said while she searched for a stand at Mansel Road Market, she lived with her neighbour in a flat in the CDB.“While I waited for a stand, I used to sell on the streets,” she said.She said after she finally got the stand, she could be there full time.“With the money I make, I’ve been able to educate my children and they have finished high school and now are doing part- time work.“I hope one day they will find good jobs.” She said it’s important for women to do things for themselves.“I didn’t want to leave my house, but because my children had to go to school I didn’t have a choice.” She said she buys material to make the skirts and cuts and sews them herself to fit different sizes. “In September I get a lot of orders because people buy them for their girls who go to the Zulu reed dance.” 
